Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Wednesday!=20
There=E2=80=99s something electric happening. Optimism is spreading. People=
 are doing big things. And you can, too.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Ambition=E2=80=99s Gravity
Tell me, what is it you plan to do
with your one wild and precious life?
=E2=80=94Mary Oliver
Aside from the doomers who believe that AI will kill us all and the techno-=
utopians who believe it will solve all of our problems, there are three mai=
n ways that people seem to be thinking about AI.=C2=A0
At one extreme, you might fear that AI will take your job. Certainly, you=
=E2=80=99ve read as much in the press, and it does seem to be getting bette=
r and better at the things you=E2=80=99re paid to do. On this extreme, AI i=
s scary.=C2=A0
In the middle, you might feel AI FOMO, feel that you need to =E2=80=9Clearn=
 AI=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cleverage AI=E2=80=9D because everyone else is doin=
g it and you don=E2=80=99t want to miss out. From this position, AI is over=
whelming: how can you ever keep up?=C2=A0
A third, far more productive approach is to first determine what you unique=
ly want to accomplish with your life, and then view everything, including A=
I, through the lens of whether it helps you accomplish your goal. From this=
 perspective, AI is a tool and you are the one who wields.=C2=A0
You can wait for the Sandworm to swallow you whole or set a thumper, grab y=
our hooks, and ride it.=C2=A0
Would a practically free army of near-genius employees help you accomplish =
the one thing you want to accomplish? Is GPT-4 or Claude 3 or Gemini 1.5 Pr=
o or Mistral Lage better at what you need it to do? Or is each better at on=
e particular thing you need them to do? Oh! Look, this new model just dropp=
ed and it seems like it solves exactly the thing I=E2=80=99m looking to sol=
ve. I=E2=80=99ll hire that one, too.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s more than just AI, though. We are lucky enough to be alive in =
the most incredible time in human history. Beyond AI, people are making rap=
id progress across a number of fields at the same time: space, manufacturin=
g, robotics, energy, bio, crypto.=C2=A0
All that progress can be overwhelming or empowering, and which of those two=
 it is is entirely up to you.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m here to tell you: you can simply decide to do big things.=C2=A0
And I=E2=80=99m here to argue that you should spend the time to figure out =
the most ambitious thing you could dream of doing with your one wild and pr=
ecious life.=C2=A0
When you name your ambition, it seems that the world conspires to help you =
achieve it, because you become more aware of all the tools at your disposal=
=2E=C2=A0
In naming your ambition, name something big, something you can uniquely ach=
ieve.
You=E2=80=99re lucky enough to be alive at a time when the world is buildin=
g new, more powerful tools to help you achieve your goal at a faster clip t=
han it ever has.=C2=A0
Let me get more specific, with something small that I have experienced so m=
any times that I know it to be true.=C2=A0
I read in two modes: aimlessly or with a goal.=C2=A0
When I=E2=80=99m reading aimlessly, I simply enjoy the words and the storie=
s. Maybe I learn something that influences my thinking, or gives me an idea=
 for an essay, or tucks away into my subconscious to surface when the time =
is right. But it=E2=80=99s a form of entertainment. It=E2=80=99s a passive =
thing.=C2=A0
Reading with a goal is a different experience altogether. When I have an id=
ea for an essay in mind, useful nuggets jump off the page. Not just the pag=
e. In everything I watch, listen to, see, in every conversation I have, eve=
ry daydream, every otherwise-mindless Twitter scroll, some relevant tidbit =
leaps out.=C2=A0
Every experience becomes more active when I have a goal in mind, I become m=
ore active. More aware.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
Take this essay.=C2=A0
I had the idea for the essay on Saturday morning, then I wrote a few of the=
 paragraphs you just read, then I scrolled Twitter as a form of plausibly p=
roductive procrastination. Within one minute, I kid you not, I saw three hi=
ghly relevant tweets.=C2=A0
In the very first paragraph of Self-Reliance [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/d24fd0a0-2d9d-43cd-ad6b-cccf87be945c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Emerson writes:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CTo believe our own thought, to believe that what is true for you i=
n your private heart is true for all men, -- that is genius. Speak your lat=
ent conviction, and it shall be the universal sense; for the inmost in due =
time becomes the outmost.=E2=80=9D
I mean, come on.=C2=A0
I realize now that I might be talking about what some call *~manifestation~=
*. So be it. I=E2=80=99ve come to believe that woo woo has a basis in reali=
ty; I=E2=80=99ve lived this particular woo woo in my writing process.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
This is its mechanism: name your aim, and you will be more aware of the thi=
ngs that might help you achieve it. It=E2=80=99s that simple, like directed=
 Baader-Meinhof [ https://substack.com/redirect/72f491b0-91b5-4708-a83f-f29=
3dab8fda0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ]. No magic required.=C2=A0
Now, we=E2=80=99re talking about an essay here. Small potatoes. But it work=
s at more consequential scales, too.=C2=A0
When you have an idea for a product you want to build, for a community you =
want to form, for anything you really and truly want to make exist in the w=
orld, when you can=E2=80=99t stop thinking about making it exist, the tools=
 you=E2=80=99ll need start appearing. New technologies, research, even peop=
le. The world becomes a menu.=C2=A0
It may even work better the more consequential the scale, if you need other=
s to join you on your quest. There=E2=80=99s a simple reason for that, too.=
=C2=A0
Ambition is like mass. The more you have, the stronger your gravitational p=
ull.=C2=A0
Read any account of working at SpaceX or talk to anyone who=E2=80=99s worke=
d there. It sounds brutally hard. And yet, SpaceX is one of the most highly=
 sought after employers in the world, in large part because of Elon=E2=80=
=99s ambition to take humans off this world. Only one group of people will =
be the first to make humans multiplanetary.=C2=A0
Those who met him still speak of Steve Jobs=E2=80=99 reality distortion fie=
ld, nearly thirteen years after his death. His ambition warped the fabric o=
f reality around his goals.=C2=A0
Satoshi Nakamoto pseudonymously wrote [ https://substack.com/redirect/26934=
546-5b23-487d-a855-66490362031d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that individuals could rebuild the financial syst=
em with their computers, and sixteen years later, millions have rallied to =
the leaderless cause.
I have a sneaking suspicion that the rumors [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/395fee0e-3bb7-41a4-8153-32fae28e1d32?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of Sam Altman=E2=80=99s $7 trillion fundrai=
se to build the chips to power AGI has made recruiting at OpenAI even easie=
r.=C2=A0
For a budding example, study what=E2=80=99s happening in El Segundo [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/f181f9df-6a15-4a1e-9e5e-ba8cc0a13033?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. A group of twenty-=
somethings are telling anyone who will listen that it=E2=80=99s possible to=
 do seemingly impossible things, like control the weather [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/f7bf010d-af7c-42ab-9971-a70fcc2c0179?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or turn nuclear into hydrocar=
bons [ https://substack.com/redirect/1e1516df-d64a-4b01-badc-d457c10ac5da?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and pe=
ople are starting to believe. Their ambition attracted young engineers from=
 around the country to fly out to California for a Defense Tech Hackathon, =
for no pay and on their own dime.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s no surprise that Ernest Shackleton=E2=80=99s ad, real or not, =
has resonated through generations.=C2=A0
In each example, there=E2=80=99s a call: you can do big things. And there=
=E2=80=99s an admonition: you must do the biggest thing you can do with you=
r one shot.=C2=A0
But what to work on? What=E2=80=99s the biggest thing you can do with your =
one shot?=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a question only you can answer, based on your talents and yo=
ur own definition of =E2=80=9Cbig.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s no right answer=
=2E You don=E2=80=99t have to cure cance=
r. I write a free newsletter.=C2=A0
One way to start thinking about it is by asking yourself what you would do =
if you had all the resources in the world, because increasingly, you will.=
=C2=A0
Much is made of the fact that a common person today consumes products that =
kings and queens of old could never have imagined =E2=80=93 iPhones, televi=
sions, air conditioners, cars, medicine, airplanes.=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s less well-appreciated is that the common person today has ac=
cess to tools with which to create that industrialists and CEOs of old coul=
dn=E2=80=99t have fathomed, and that the toolkit is expanding every single =
day.
With a big ambition in mind, it=E2=80=99s like you have 8 billion people =
=E2=80=93 and soon countless more digital ones =E2=80=93 working to provide=
 you with exactly what you need to do the thing you were put on this earth =
to do. You have the world=E2=80=99s best entrepreneurs, scientists, and res=
earchers working to build things that make your thing cheaper and more powe=
rful. Their outputs become your inputs. What an unbelievable gift.=C2=A0
In this direct way - outputs becoming inputs =E2=80=93 and in a less tangib=
le but equally impactful way, ambition is contagious.=C2=A0
SpaceX was the four-minute mile for deep tech. It inspired (and trained) a =
generation of founders to go build things harder than they previously thoug=
ht possible. That generation is inspiring a new generation. Elon memed the =
current deep tech explosion into existence, and the meme is spreading.=C2=
=A0
Optimism shapes reality [ https://substack.com/redirect/7a449076-7abc-4953-=
8d43-a695796181e7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], and it sets off a chain reaction. It bounces into people, unle=
ashing their energy and firing their own optimism into the next person to u=
nleash more energy and more optimism.=C2=A0
This reaction is underway now. You can feel it. There=E2=80=99s been a vibe=
 shift.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m here to tell you that you can, even must, take part.=C2=A0
If you have some time today, this weekend, or in the coming weeks, spend so=
me of it thinking through what it is you want to do. Name it, give it a sha=
pe and weight.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not saying you need to awaken AGI or commercialize fusion. I wr=
ite a free newsletter, who am I to tell you what big means for you?
As Isaac Asimov wrote [ https://substack.com/redirect/d2db0554-10d4-4266-90=
d8-ed8cbabb425f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] half a century ago:=C2=A0
Is the individual person wise enough to know what he or she can best do? =
=E2=80=94Why not? Who else can know? And what can a person do best except t=
hat which he or she wants to do most?=C2=A0
What I can tell you is that you have the agency to do something bigger than=
 you think possible. You can simply decide to do it, and the world will ben=
d itself to help you.=C2=A0
A couple of weeks ago, I spent time in San Francisco, a place where you can=
 practically see ambition=E2=80=99s chain reaction with your own eyes. I wa=
s talking to a founder about a challenge I was thinking through, and after =
half a second of thought, she told me, essentially: =E2=80=9CYou need to go=
 much bigger.=E2=80=9D
That sparked something in me, changed the way I approach the world. It gave=
 me new confidence and raised my ambition. As I=E2=80=99ve pursued that amb=
ition over the past couple of weeks, everything I=E2=80=99ve written about =
in this piece started happening. I=E2=80=99ve noticed the right tools mater=
ialize, pulled co-conspirators I have no business co-conspiring with into m=
y orbit, and felt more energized than I have in a long time. We=E2=80=99ll =
see what happens, but it feels good.=C2=A0
In the meantime, I=E2=80=99m passing that spark on to you.=C2=A0
Name your ambition. Make it big, something worthy of your unique talents. A=
pproach the chaos of change with the clarity of purpose. Don=E2=80=99t let =
the machines take your job; put them to work for you.=C2=A0
You only live once, and you get to live in the most magical time.
So tell me, what is it you plan to do with your one wild and precious life?
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/80a4a419-5d4e-4566-9853-5ac27=
aff8e36?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and Claude 3 for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

